Supplementary code documentation for scViewer manuscript.

scViewer: An interactive single-cell gene expression visualization tool

Abhijeet R. Patil*, Gaurav Kumar, Huanyu Zhou, Liling Warren

SCD Statistics, Teva Pharmaceuticals

In this document, we show the single-cell data processing workflow and storing metadata information into the Seurat object to make it available to use in the app.

Section 1- Load packages/libraries for processing single-cell data

The methods/tools we incorporated in this single-cell data processing script are popularly used methods in single-cell field. Users can use other packages that contain different methodologies for loading, pre-processing, normalization, doublet finding, and annotation steps. The only requirement for running the app is the proper naming protocol for columns in the metadata information which is highlighted in the below workflow.

Here, we will load the required libraries for the processing the data. The Seurat and sctransform packages are used for processing the data. We used the scDblFinder package for identifying and removing doublets in the dataset. Finally, we used the marker based scSorter method for annotating the cells.

First, we will load the count matrices for individual samples and preprocess the data to create Seurat object.

The Seurat object initialization step where the min.cells- parameter will include genes detected in at least 3 cells. The min.features - Include cells where at least 200 genes are detected.

for(x in dirs){
  # name <- gsub('_filtered_feature_bc_matrix','', x)

  cts <- ReadMtx(mtx = paste0('./',x,'/matrix.mtx.gz'),
                 features = paste0('./',x,'/features.tsv.gz'),
                 cells = paste0('./',x,'/barcodes.tsv.gz'))

  # create seurat objects
  assign(x, CreateSeuratObject(counts = cts, min.cells = 3, min.features = 200))
}
## as(<dgTMatrix>, "dgCMatrix") is deprecated since Matrix 1.5-0; do as(., "CsparseMatrix") instead

Section 3- Metadata information for running the shiny app

Add metadata Important for the scViewer shiny app

Here, we will add three new columns to the Seurat metadata.

1. Column name for disease state- grp. For ex, This column will have samples such as AD and NC which represents Alzheimer disease patients and normal controls.

2. Column name for samples- sample_ids. For ex, This column will have samples such as AD_1, AD_2, NC_1, NC_2 etc. which represents two disease and two healthy patients.

3. Column name for cell types- cell_type. For ex, This column will have cell types such as Astrocytes, Microglia etc.

Below we add the 1 and 2 from above. The cell types will be added in the cell annotation section.

## Add metadata information
## Add metadata information
## create a tmp_sample column (Extract from rownames- the above merge function stores the samples in the order inserted in the vector)
merged_data$tmp_sample <- rownames(merged_data@meta.data)

## split sample column to create unique IDs (sample) and disease state (grp) columns.
merged_data@meta.data <- separate(merged_data@meta.data, col = 'tmp_sample', into = c('grp', 'sample', 'barcode'),
                                    sep = '_')

## Add unique sample IDs and disease state information to create a new sample_ids column
merged_data$sample_ids <- c(paste0(merged_data$grp, "_", merged_data$sample))

merged_data@meta.data$sample<- NULL

Pre-processing the data based on information from above steps

The nFeature_RNA and nCount_RNA represents the number of genes detected in each cell and the total number of molecules (UMIs) detected within a cell respectively. While the low nFeature_RNA in a cell mean that it may be dead/dying or it may represent an empty droplet, the high nCount_RNA and nFeature_RNA denotes that the cell may be a doublet or multiplet. This filtering along with mitochondrial reads is crucial pre-processing step, because, removing such outliers from these groups might also remove some of the doublets or dead/empty droplets.

Remove all the potential doublets found

The cell being either doublet or singlet is stored in column scDlFinder.class. The potential doublets are removed in this step.

# After doublet removal
merged_data_v1 <- subset(merged_data_seurat, subset = scDblFinder.class  == "singlet")

Subset Data

The final data after removing potential doublets and subsetting based on nFeature and percent.mt is shown below

merged_data_new <- subset(merged_data_v1, subset = nFeature_RNA > 200 & nFeature_RNA < 7500
                   & percent.mt < 15
                   & nCount_RNA < 75000
)

Section 3- Normalizing and scaling the data

SCT: Single Cell Transform

The SCTransform method is an one stop alternative to the NormalizeData, FindVariableFeatures, ScaleData workflow of Seurat. This function is used to normalize the counts that measures the differences in sequencing depth per cell for each sample. The SCT method uses regularized negative binomial model to perform both normalization and variance stabilization of single-cell RNA-seq data. The SCTransform method removes the variation due to sequencing depth (nUMIs). In addition, the parameter vars.to.regress regresses out the variation from other sources such as percentage of mitochondrial. The output of SCT model is the normalized expression levels for all the transcripts. Lastly, the variable.features.n parameter is used to set the number of variable features. The default value is 3000 genes.

merged_data_new_sct <- SCTransform(merged_data_new, method = "glmGamPoi", variable.features.n = 3000, vars.to.regress = "percent.mt", conserve.memory = TRUE, verbose = FALSE)
rm(merged_data_new)
gc()
##              used    (Mb) gc trigger    (Mb)   max used    (Mb)
## Ncells    8790961   469.5   17170554   917.1   17170554   917.1
## Vcells 1927478370 14705.5 5125004154 39100.7 5124988398 39100.6

Run UMAP

The Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection (UMAP) dimensional reduction technique is run on the first 20 principal components.

merged_data_new_sct <- RunUMAP(merged_data_new_sct, dims = 1:20, verbose = FALSE)

Find Neighbors

Here we compute the k nearest neighbors in the dataset. The nearest neighbors are calculated on the reduced dimensions from the PCA. We use first 20 principal components.

merged_data_new_sct <- FindNeighbors(merged_data_new_sct, dims = 1:20, verbose = FALSE)

Find Clusters

Once we have calculated the k-nearest neighbors in previous step, we will find the clusters of cells by the shared nearest neihbor (SNN) clustering algorithm. Here, we have set the resolution as 0.8. The higher resolution usually gives more number of clusters.

merged_data_new_sct <- FindClusters(merged_data_new_sct, resolution = 0.8, method = "igraph", verbose = FALSE)
gc()

Section 4- Cell Annotation

Here we used the scSorter: single cell Sorter which is a popularly used marker based cell type annotation method.

Users might use different approaches such as FindMarkers function from Seurat or reference based annotation methods such as SingleR etc. Please keep the column name as cell_type in the metadata while using any annotation method.

Loading marker genes data

anno <- read.csv("./anno.csv")

The scSorter method is a semi-supervised learning algorithm which expects the pre-processed data as input. The normalized and transformed expression matrix generated by SCT method is given as input. The scSorter method also allows to incorporate top variable genes selected by SCT method to be used as input.

expr <- merged_data_new_sct@assays$SCT@data
topgenes <- head(merged_data_new_sct@assays$SCT@var.features, 3000)
topgene_filter = rowSums(expr[topgenes, ]!=0) > ncol(expr)*.1
topgenes = topgenes[topgene_filter]

## Subset the pre-processed expression data and run scSorter method.
picked_genes = unique(c(anno$Marker, topgenes))
expr = expr[rownames(expr) %in% picked_genes, ]

Apply the scSorter method (fit)

Fit the scSorter method with the parameters as expression matrix and marker genes. The predicted cell type assignment results are stored in the rts object.

rts <- scSorter(expr, anno)
merged_data_new_sct$cell_type <- rts$Pred_Type
gc()

Preparing the data for plotting cell type composition across different disease groups.
